{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17474896","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17474896"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:26:06+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:26:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12448"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12448","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12448"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.27,0.13,0.08,0.43]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4956"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47756"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4956","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4956"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12448"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"32486"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1086"},{"type":"tags","id":"1155"},{"type":"tags","id":"1575"},{"type":"tags","id":"4487"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8135"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9154"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12667"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43330"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44126"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47756","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/47756"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA seven-year-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-week history of facial swelling. This started with swelling around the eyes and was more noticeable in the mornings. Over the past two weeks, he has had an intermittent fever, and his mother has noticed that he has not been urinating as often as usual. She brought her child to the clinic five weeks ago, and the initial examination revealed bilateral pedal and facial oedema, along with a distended abdomen. At that time, the urine dipstick showed protein 3+ but no blood. The child was prescribed prednisolone at a standard dose for four weeks, but there has been no change in his condition, and if anything, his symptoms have become more severe.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with a pulse rate of 90/min, blood pressure 110/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. His face and legs are swollen. Abdominal examination reveals ascites.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum albumin: 22 g/L (35-50)\u003Cbr\u003ESerum creatinine: 60 \u03bcmol/L (20-80)\u003Cbr\u003EUrine protein:creatinine ratio: 350 mg/mmol (\u0026lt;20)\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Increase dose of prednisolone","Evaluation for underlying infections or other systemic diseases","Supportive care with diuretics and dietary modifications","Plasmapheresis","Referral for genetic testing and renal biopsy"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis child presents with classic features of nephrotic syndrome: edema, proteinuria, and hypoalbuminemia. The most appropriate next step in management is \u003Cstrong\u003Ereferral for genetic testing and renal biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E. This is because the child has not responded to a four-week course of standard-dose prednisolone, which defines steroid-resistant nephrotic syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe urinalysis shows significant proteinuria (3+ on dipstick and urine protein:creatinine ratio of 350 mg/mmol) without hematuria. This pattern is typical for nephrotic syndrome and less consistent with acute post-streptococcal glomerulonephritis (APSGN), which typically presents with hematuria, red cell casts, and often hypertension.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreasing the dose of prednisolone\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate as the child has already failed to respond to a standard course, indicating steroid resistance. Continuing high-dose steroids without a clear diagnosis may lead to unnecessary side effects.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEvaluation for underlying infections or other systemic diseases\u003C/strong\u003E is less likely to be helpful at this stage. While infections can trigger nephrotic syndrome, the persistent nature of symptoms despite steroid treatment suggests a primary renal pathology.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESupportive care with diuretics and dietary modifications\u003C/strong\u003E may help manage symptoms but does not address the underlying cause. These measures are typically used in conjunction with specific treatment for nephrotic syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPlasmapheresis\u003C/strong\u003E is not a first-line treatment for nephrotic syndrome and would not be considered without a specific diagnosis from a renal biopsy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGenetic testing and renal biopsy are crucial in steroid-resistant nephrotic syndrome to identify the underlying cause, which could include conditions like focal segmental glomerulosclerosis, minimal change disease, or genetic forms of nephrotic syndrome. The results will guide appropriate treatment and provide prognostic information.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["For childhood nephrotic syndrome, a renal biopsy is indicated for steroid resistance.","Nephrotic syndrome is characterized by proteinuria, hypoalbuminemia, edema, and hyperlipidemia."],"references":["Tapia C, Bashir K. Nephrotic Syndrome. [Updated 2022 Jun 5]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2022 Jan-.","Sachdeva, S. et al. (2021) Management of steroid-resistant nephrotic syndrome in children, Cureus."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"32486"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12448"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"32486","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/32486"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-06-28T12:01:56+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-06-28T12:02:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4956"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47756"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"Nephrology","synonyms":["Renal"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:52:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"